## Intro & Rationale

Currently we have implementation for `EventCounter` class which is used to collect metrics like request per second. However the design of this API is not as flexible as it could be, and for different kinds of counters / metrics, the current `EventCounter` API doesn't work very well for various reasons (specific examples detailed below). 

This proposal includes 3 new APIs that are variants of the current `EventCounter` class - namely `PollingCounter`, `IncrementingEventCounter`, and `IncrementingPollingCounter`. 

## New API Description

### EventCounter

Proposing two public surface additions to `EventCounter`:

- `public string DisplayName { get; set; }`

This is a property that will be displayed in the payload for the EventCounter. This is a property a user can set if the user wants a separate field that represents how this counter should be displayed on a viewer, if it is different from the name of this counter. For example, a counter may be instantiated with a name "request-counter", and its `DisplayName` property can be set to "Number of Requests" which would be a more viewer-friendly name. This is useful when trying to create counters that interact with the CLI, where having spaces in the name might cause trouble or confusion for the CLI parser and the user.

- `public void AddMetaData(string key, string value)`

This API adds a key-value pair of "MetaData" to an instance of `EventCounter`. This API exists so that users can add any metadata about their counter that may not be relevant for all `EventCounter` instances. A user can add arbitrary number of metadata to their `EventCounter` instance, and it will be reported as part of the `EventCounter` payload by a comma-separated string. For example, suppose the user wants to categorize his/her counters into different tiers of counters in terms of priority - they can use this API to encode that information into their `EventCounter` instances:

```
    anImportantCounter.AddmetaData("priority", "1");
    notAnImportantCounter.AddMetaData("priority", "3");
```


### PollingCounter
```
class PollingCounter {
    PollingCounter(string name, EventSource eventSource Func<float> getMetricFunction);
    string DisplayName;
    void AddMetaData(string key, string value);
}
```

`PollingCounter` is a class that will be used for similar kind of metrics to those that can be represented by `EventCounter`, but it takes in a callback function as a parameter to its constructor, which is used to gather metrics instead of the client having to explicitly call `WriteMetric` - this is what you need to do for instances of `EventCounter`. Explicit calls to `WriteMetric` may not be so nice for certain kinds of metrics because some metrics vary over time in a continuous manner, and it is not always clear at what discrete interval the value needs to be polled and written from the user's side. For example, GC heap size varies over time, but user may not know (and should not be) querying the heap size 15 times a second to keep track of this. `PollingCounter` allows user to get reports on the value without needing to explicitly update the value at an arbitrary time interval of user's choice. 

When the EventSource that the instance of `PollingCounter` is attached to is enabled, it will then call the callback function per every interval it needs to report the values. 

A user who wants to monitor his/her app's GC heap size can create an instance of `PollingCounter` like this:

```
    PollingCounter gcHeapCounter = new PollingCounter("GC Heap Size", myEventSource, () => GC.GetTotalMemory(false));
```

A viewer that displays PollingCounter would be able to display a metric for every interval that it requested the samples to be taken (via the `EventCounterIntervalSec` argument).


### IncrementingEventCounter
```
class IncrementingEventCounter {
    IncrementingEventCounter(string name, EventSource eventSource);
    string DisplayName;
    TimeSpan DisplayRateTimeScale;
    void Increment(float increment = 1);
    void AddMetaData(string key, string value);
}
```

`IncrementingEventCounter` is a counter that generates a slightly different metric than `EventCounter`. `EventCounter` reports various statistics per each interval it reports such as min, max, mean, median, and standard deviation. However, for certain values, we might want to capture just the sum of increments over an interval. For example, the number of exceptions thrown is an incrementing value, and we don't want to take an average on the "# of exceptions" thrown per interval because it will be meaningless. What we really want is "how many exceptions were thrown since I last reported that value", and that is what `IncrementingEventCounter` is for.

A counter that keeps track of exceptions that happened in a user's app can be implemented as an `IncrementingEventCounter` like this:

```
...
    IncrementingEventCounter exceptionCounter = new IncrementingEventCounter("exception-counter", myEventSource);
...

public void someRoutine()
{
    try
    {
        // some code
    }
    catch (ArgumentException)
    {
    	exceptionCounter.Increment();
    }
}
...

```

`IncrementingEventCounter` reports in its payload the total number of increment that happened since it last reported the value. For example, if `EventCounterIntervalSec` was set to 3 seconds, it would display how many increments happened in the past 3 seconds.


`IncrementingEventCounter` has a public property called `DisplayRateTimeScale` - this can be set if the user wants to specify that this counter should be aggregated at a particular rate. For example, a simple viewer might want to show this counter (# of exceptions) as # of exceptions per second, or per hour. The viewer needs to know a certain timescale that represents the rate at which it should be displayed.


### IncrementingPollingCounter
```
class IncrementingPollingCounter {
    IncrementingPollingCounter(string name, EventSource eventSource, Func<float> getCountFunction);
    string DisplayName;
    TimeSpan DisplayRateTimeScale;
    void AddMetaData(string key, string value);
}
```

`IncrementingPollingCounter` is a similar type of counter to `IncrementingEventCounter` in that it aggregates values over an interval, but like `PollingCounter`, it takes in callback function to update the counter value instead of having the user explicitly call `Increment` on it. This allows the flexibility of `PollingCounter` for a metric whose value may change in a continuous manner.

